{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2b273f10-be99-48dc-93b6-76d60b22efba","content":"Here's how to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app in a Windows container on K8s:\n\n**1. Exec into the container:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n**2. Install `dotnet-trace` inside the container:**\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n```\n\n**3. Find your process ID:**\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**4. Collect the trace:**\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file. Copy it out with:\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:<path/to/trace.nettrace> ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**5. Analyze** by opening the `.nettrace` in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or convert to Speedscope format:\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope\n```\n\n> **Tip:** If you can't install tools in the container, use a [sidecar/ephemeral debug container](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/diagnostics/dotnet-trace) or enable the `EventPipe` via environment variables (`DOTNET_EnableEventPipe=1`, `DOTNET_EventPipeOutputPath=/tmp/trace.nettrace`) and restart the pod.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"24feb069-dcd3-4982-b2fa-5b4d58105c40","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes. This is a knowledge/advisory question, not a code task. I should provide concise, actionable steps.","outputTokens":420},"id":"ef494891-d71b-49d8-923d-d68334a773fb","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:48:23.960Z","parentId":"c621673c-5e32-4502-82f6-a969eb1adb9c"}
